I can't really parse it together but there is a theme in Twin Peaks about coffee and how when the Black Lodge starts to consume a character their teeth turn black, e.g. Windom Earle towards the end is shown with black teeth, and it has to do with coffee staining your teeth black.

There are scenes where in the Black Lodge agent Cooper's coffee is changed into some sort of black oil and oil is a symbol popular in Hollywood and media always associated with corruption, decay, death, etc. Some on a 2000s forum connect the black teeth to "Black Jack" gum brand.

Supposedly the original Black Jack gum used to color your teeth black because it contained black licorice, fits with that "that gum you like is coming back in style" cryptic line. And (no relation to the plot of course) black licorice is the textbook example of estrogenic plants.

There is a long blogpost to be written about how electricity functions in Twin Peaks, how e.g. the dwarf resides in the electricity and uses it to travel, and "dirty electricity" in the real world that Danny Roddy was obsessed with and said it could attract fire ants and insects.

It pops up in Juenger's Waldgang also with a remark about antennae above cities provoking contact with the demonic. I guess there's a persistent idea about (dirty) electricity and other immaterial, "aerial" psychic forces somehow inviting infestations of parasites, pests, demons.

I think in many Slavic languages demons used to be called "rabies" too and the disease, demon possessions, and other kinds of mental insanity were seen as one thing. So the rabies hydrophobia means demons are scared of water and doctors used to treat crazy people with cold baths.

Final Twin Peaks post but someone pointed out that only when the sprinkler systems goes off BOB's spirit starts slamming his head into the wall and finally leaves Leland and it reminds me of the connection between demon possession and rabies that existed in the past.
